$http.jsonp works because underneath it just adds a script element to the DOM with the URL of its src attribute set to the request URL from your code. That works cross-origin because the browser allows script elements to have a src attribute with a URL from a different origin. So unlike $http.get, $http.jsonp doesn‚Äôt call XHR behind the scenes. That‚Äôs why $http.jsonp works in this case even though the server the request is sent to doesn‚Äôt support CORS. The $http.get request fails because it uses XHR and for that to work, the server the request goes to must support CORS.

new Date(moment().format('YYYY,MM,DD')) makes no sense. It creates a date, outputs a string in "YYYY,MM,DD" format (e.g. "2017,08,31"), passes that to the Date constructor, which then attempts to parse the string. It is highly likely that the last parse will fail (it does in Safari at least). If you want a Date set to the start of the current day, then moment().startOf('day').toDate() will do the job.

Using underscore as the input argument for anonymous functions like this one means you can only use that unnamed argument once - if you try to use it twice (e.g. (_.Id, _.Order)) you're actually creating an anonymous function that takes two arguments (with the first underscore referencing the first one, and the second underscore referencing the second). This is obviously not what we need here. In other words - naming the argument (here, I named it record - could have used any name that makes sense) is often a must. Underscode is short-hand that should be used carefully.
